         <abstract>
            <p>Can monetary policy affect the stock market directly -- without first influencing either the economy or investor expectations? Although an increasing number of monetarists think it can, they have yet to explain how, at the beginning of an expansion, when stocks are making their most dramatic gains, monetary ease can improve the liquidity of common stock investors. (It can obviously affect bank liquidity, but banks do not own stock directly.) The author offers an explanation.</p>
          </abstract>
